case_names: Siegel v. Univ. of Cincinnati College of Med.
summaries: Civil immunity. The magistrate found that defendant's employee, a physician, was acting on behalf of the state, he did not act with malicious purpose, in bad faith, or in a wanton or reckless manner during his treatment and care of plaintiff's decedent. As a result, the physician was entitled to immunity pursuant to R.C. 9.86 and 2743.02(F) and the courts of common pleas did not have jurisdiction over any civil actions that could be filed against the physician upon the allegations of that case.
